The Jamia Masjid is a place of worship for the university's students, staff, and the local Muslim community. It serves as a center for religious activities, including daily prayers, Friday congregational prayers (Jummah), and other Islamic events. The mosque's architecture reflects a blend of traditional and modern Islamic designs, and it holds significance as a spiritual and cultural hub within the university campus.

featured_reviews.review_id: Eidgah or Idgah, also Eid Gah or Id Gah (Persian: `ydgh "site of Eid [observances]"; Urdu: `yd gh; Hindi: iidgaah; Bengali: iidgaah) is a term used in South Asian Islamic culture for the open-air enclosure usually outside the city (or at the outskirts) reserved for Eid prayers offered in the morning of Eid al-Fitr and Eid al-Adha. It is usually a public place that is not used for prayers at other times of the year.[1] On the day of Eid, the first thing Muslims do in the morning is gather usually at a large open ground and offer special prayers,[2][3] in accordance with the Sunnah (traditions of Muhammad).[4] Although the usage of the term Eidgah is of Indian origin, it may be used for the musalla, the open space outside a mosque, or other open grounds where Eid prayers are performed, due to the lack of a specific Islamic term for a site of Eid observance. The Eidgah is mentioned in the famous Bengali poem by Kazi Nazrul Islam, O Mon Romzaner Oi Rozar Sheshe.

featured_reviews.review_translated_text: Pipleshwar Mahadev Temple is situated in Mohalla Swar Khas. Being the oldest temple of Swar, it is also known as Bada Mandir. The temple was established 267 years before the year 2018 with the settlement of Swar Nagar. Many Vaishnava and Digambara saints have lived at the temple, including Baba Laxman Das, Baba Sundar Das, Siddhamurti Tyagi Baba alias Elaichi Baba, Aughad Baba Lakkadgiri, Baba Dwarikdas, Taapsee Baba, Haripuri Baba, Shrimahant Ramgiri, Baba Gokul etc. Tapasi Baba's tomb is on the north side of the temple. The temple has huge idols of Mahamrityunjaya Mahadev, Mahakali, Lakshmi, Radha Krishna, Santoshi Maa, Vishnu Lakshmi, Shri Ram Darbar, Ashtabhuja Durga Maa, Shani Dev. The big temple symbolizes the amazing power of Mahadev and the fulfillment of wishes.
